In order to replace the subclass with a delegate, you can use an interface and set it as default in your super class (Order). Here is how we could do this using Java's functional interfaces for delegation of methods between classes. 

```java
interface DaysToShipCalculator { int getDaysToShip(); }
class Warehouse implements DaysToShipCalculator {} // Implementing the interface here, you can add more functionality as per your requirement in this class if needed (like a method to calculate shipment cost etc.) 
// Similarly for PriorityPlan and Order classes. You need an implementation of these interfaces based on their requirements too.  
class WarehouseImpl implements DaysToShipCalculator { public int getDaysToShip() { return /*calculation logic here*/; }} // Implementing the interface methods 
// In your super class (Order), you can set this delegate as default implementation and call it whenever needed.  
class Order{ protected WarehouseImpl warehouse = new Warehouse(); public int getDaysToShip() { return warehouse.getDaysToShip(); }} // Using the interface here 
// Similarly for PriorityOrder class, you can use this delegate in your subclasses too if needed (like a method to set priority plan etc.)  
class PriorityPlanImpl implements DaysToShipCalculator{ public int getDaysToShip() { return /*calculation logic*/; }} // Implementing the interface methods 
// In super class, you can use this delegate in your subclasses too if needed (like a method to set priority plan etc.)  
class PriorityOrder extends Order { protected PriorityPlanImpl priorityPlan = new PriorityPlan(); public int getDaysToShip() { return priorityPlan.getDaysToShip(); }} // Using the interface here 
```
This way, you can use delegation to reduce code duplications and make your classes more flexible in terms of functionality (you just need one implementation for each class). The delegate will call methods from its own or other implementers based on what it needs. This is a common pattern used when dealing with interfaces that have multiple method signatures but different behavior within them, like the DaysToShipCalculator interface above which has two versions: Warehouse and PriorityPlan (each implementing their respective functionality).

