In Java, we can use inheritance to achieve this. We'll first define an abstract base class `Employee` and then subclass it with specific types of employees (like Developer or Manager). Here is how you could do that in your codebase using the Factory Design Pattern approach which provides a way for creating objects without specifying their exact class:

```java
public interface Employee {  // Define an Interface to be shared by all employee classes.  
    String getName();     // All employees have names, so define this as part of our common superclass (Employees).
}

// Now we can create subclasses for each type: Developer and Manager...etc.. using the Employee interface 
public class Developer implements Employee {  
    private String name;     // All developers have a specific set of attributes.     

    public Developer(String n) {       
         this.name =n ;         
    }          

    @Override             
    public String getName()  {               return "Developer: ".concat(this.name);            // Return a string representation of the developer's name...etc..  
}    
```     
Then you can use this factory method to create an employee based on type code (e.g., 'D') or any other specific subclass, like `Manager`: 
public Employee createEmployee(String name, String role) {    // Role is the "type" parameter...etc..  
        if ("D".equalsIgnoreCase(role))      return new Developer (name);     else       throw new IllegalArgumentException("Invalid employee type");         } 
```          This way you can create different types of employees and still use a common interface to refer them. The advantage is that the code remains clean, modularized with interfaces for ease in refactoring or adding more roles later on without affecting existing implementations (like `Manager`).   You could also add other specific subclasses like Manager if needed based upon your requirements...etc..

